From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: OpenWrt <noreply@openwrt.org>
Date: Sat, 19 Jul 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] wifi: mt76: npu: always call check_skb on RX packets

mt76_npu_check_ppe() currently only calls airoha_ppe_dev_check_skb()
when the NPU reports CRSN = HIT_UNBIND_RATE_REACHED.  This reason code
requires an existing UNBIND entry in the HW PPE table.  After a WiFi
roaming event tears down the old flow entry, the HW PPE slot is INVALID
and the NPU reports CRSN = MISS instead -- so check_skb is never called,
and the new flow is never committed to hardware.

The wired QDMA path does not have this restriction: it calls
check_skb(rx_wlan=false) unconditionally for every received packet.
The check_skb function itself has a built-in rate limit (HZ/10 throttle
per hash slot) so there is no performance concern from calling it on
every packet.

Remove the CRSN reason gate so that WiFi NPU RX always calls check_skb,
matching the wired path behavior.  This allows the PPE driver to
re-commit torn-down flows when the client reconnects after roaming.

Signed-off-by: OpenWrt <noreply@openwrt.org>
---
--- a/npu.c
+++ b/npu.c
@@ -117,7 +117,7 @@
 			u32 info)
 {
 	struct airoha_ppe_dev *ppe_dev;
-	u16 reason, hash;
+	u16 hash;
 
 	if (!mt76_npu_device_active(dev))
 		return;
@@ -131,11 +131,8 @@
 	hash = FIELD_GET(NPU_RX_DMA_FOE_ID_MASK, info);
 	skb_set_hash(skb, hash, PKT_HASH_TYPE_L4);
 
-	reason = FIELD_GET(NPU_RX_DMA_CRSN_MASK, info);
-	if (reason == PPE_CPU_REASON_HIT_UNBIND_RATE_REACHED) {
-		skb_set_mac_header(skb, 0);
-		airoha_ppe_dev_check_skb(ppe_dev, skb, hash, true);
-	}
+	skb_set_mac_header(skb, 0);
+	airoha_ppe_dev_check_skb(ppe_dev, skb, hash, true);
 out:
 	rcu_read_unlock();
 }
